\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S\left[\phi\right]=\int_{x}\mathcal{L}\left[\phi\right]=\int_{x}\frac{1}{2}\partial_{\mu}\phi_{a}\partial^{\mu}\phi_{a}-\frac{1}{2}m^{2}\phi_{a}\phi_{a}-\frac{\lambda}{4!}\left(\phi_{a}\phi_{a}\right)^{2},
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1,\cdots,N$
\end_inset

 and we choose to operate in the spontaneous symmetry breaking regime with
 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{2}<0$
\end_inset

.
 The vacuum expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}=-6m^{2}/\lambda$
\end_inset

 and the tree level mass of the radial (``Higgs'') mode is 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}^{2}=\lambda v^{2}/3$
\end_inset

.
 We take the vacuum expectation value to be in the last component 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{a}\equiv\left\langle \phi_{a}\right\rangle =\left(0,\cdots,0,v\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The symmetry transformation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi_{a}=i\epsilon_{A}T_{ab}^{A}\phi_{b}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ab}^{A}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $A=1,\cdots,N\left(N-1\right)/2$
\end_inset

 are the generators of rotations.
 When we have cause to use specific generators we will write 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(j,k\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $j\neq k$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $1,\cdots,N$
\end_inset

 to denote the plane of rotation, and have 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ab}^{jk}=i\left(\delta_{ja}\delta_{kb}-\delta_{jb}\delta_{ka}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Considering this theory in a particle physics context, the most likely external
 perturbations will be linear or quadratic in the fields.
 For example, we could be using this theory to describe mesons coupling
 to hadrons through Yukawa interactions 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\phi\bar{\psi}\psi$
\end_inset

, or Higgs fields coupling to a Yang-Mills sector through (possibly some
 subset of) the conserved currents with terms like 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\mu A}\left(i\phi_{a}T_{ab}^{A}\overleftrightarrow{\partial_{\mu}}\phi_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\mu A}W_{\mu A}\phi_{a}\phi_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 The theory can also represent an extended Higgs or dark matter sector coupled
 via portal terms to the standard model Higgs with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\phi_{a}\phi_{a}\Phi^{\dagger}\Phi$
\end_inset

, or coupled to a standard model singlet scalar sector 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim S\phi\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Finally the fields could represent a multi-field inflaton, moduli or an
 extended gravitational sector, all of whose interactions to the standard
 model sector will be mediated by terms of the preceding forms to leading
 order in an effective field theory expansion.
 Thus, on very general grounds we expect that the external perturbation
 can be taken as a linear or quadratic function of the fields.
 The only notable exception is the coupling of the field theory to gravity,
 which includes the quartic interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\sqrt{-g}\left(\phi_{a}\phi_{a}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We now consider the notable observables in the theory.
 Chiefly we will be interested in the field expectation values 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{a}$
\end_inset

, the conserved 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 currents 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
j_{\mu}^{A}=i\left\langle \phi_{a}T_{ab}^{A}\overleftrightarrow{\partial_{\mu}}\phi_{b}\right\rangle ,
\]

\end_inset

 and the energy-momentum tensor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T_{\mu\nu} & =\left\langle \partial_{\mu}\phi_{a}\partial_{\nu}\phi_{a}\vphantom{\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)}\right.\\
 & \left.-\eta_{\mu\nu}\left(\frac{1}{2}\partial_{\rho}\phi_{a}\partial^{\rho}\phi_{a}-\frac{1}{2}m^{2}\phi_{a}\phi_{a}-\frac{\lambda}{4!}\left(\phi_{a}\phi_{a}\right)^{2}\right)\right\rangle .
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Again we see that, apart from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\phi_{a}\phi_{a}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 term in the energy, the observables are also linear or quadratic in the
 fields.
 Note that if desired 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left(\phi_{a}\phi_{a}\right)^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 can be approximated in a mean field approximation by terms of the form
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \phi\phi\right\rangle ^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \phi\phi\right\rangle \left\langle \phi\right\rangle ^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \phi\right\rangle ^{4}$
\end_inset

 plus corrections that can be found diagrammatically.
 This means that many of the local quantities one might want can be determined
 by a method yielding 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i\hbar\Delta_{ab}\equiv\left\langle \mathrm{T}\left[\phi_{a}\phi_{b}\right]\right\rangle -\varphi_{a}\varphi_{b}$
\end_inset

 subject to generic quadratic perturbations of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $-J_{a}\phi_{a}-\frac{1}{2}K_{ab}\phi_{a}\phi_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 This problem seems tailor made for the 2PIEA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The 2PIEA is defined as the double Legendre transform of the connected generatin
g functional
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W\left[J,K\right]=-i\hbar\ln Z\left[J,K\right],
\]

\end_inset

 where the partition function is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z\left[J,K\right]=\int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\right]\exp\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(S\left[\phi\right]+J_{a}\phi_{a}+\frac{1}{2}\phi_{a}K_{ab}\phi_{b}\right).
\]

\end_inset

 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{ab}=K_{ba}$
\end_inset

 are the externally applied sources coupling linearly and quadratically
 to the field respectively.
 Performing the double Legendre transform gives the 2PIEA functional 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]=W-J_{a}\frac{\delta W}{\delta J_{a}}-K_{ab}\frac{\delta W}{\delta K_{ab}},
\]

\end_inset

 where on the right hand side 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{ab}$
\end_inset

