\begin_layout Standard
In the linear response approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{ab}$
\end_inset

 no longer vanish, and we must solve equations (
\backslash
ref{eq:WI}), (
\backslash
ref{eq:si-eom-vev}) and (
\backslash
ref{eq:si-eom-delta}) to first order in the sources without any assumption
 of homogeneity.
 To do this we expand all quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\to\tilde{\varphi}+\delta\varphi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\to\tilde{\Delta}+\delta\Delta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\to\tilde{\ell}+\delta\ell$
\end_inset

 and match terms order by order, considering the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\varphi$
\end_inset

 etc.
 as first order.
 Working first on (
\backslash
ref{eq:WI}) gives the pair of equations: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =\tilde{\Delta}_{ca}^{-1}T_{ab}^{A}\tilde{\varphi}_{b},\label{eq:WI-zeroth-order}\\
0 & =\delta\Delta_{ca}^{-1}T_{ab}^{A}\tilde{\varphi}_{b}+\tilde{\Delta}_{ca}^{-1}T_{ab}^{A}\delta\varphi_{b}-J_{a}T_{ac}^{A}.\label{eq:WI-first-order}
\end{align}

\end_inset

 The first equation is simply the equilibrium constraint as expected since
 the analysis of the last section holds with all quantities decorated with
 tildes.
 The second equation is new.
 Using the identity (
\backslash
ref{eq:variation-of-inverse-delta}) gives to first order 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=-\tilde{\Delta}_{cd}^{-1}\delta\Delta_{de}\left(\tilde{\Delta}_{ea}^{-1}T_{ab}^{A}\tilde{\varphi}_{b}\right)+\tilde{\Delta}_{ca}^{-1}T_{ab}^{A}\delta\varphi_{b}-J_{a}T_{ac}^{A}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The first term vanishes by virtue of (
\backslash
ref{eq:WI-zeroth-order}), thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\Delta}_{ca}^{-1}T_{ab}^{A}\delta\varphi_{b}=J_{a}T_{ac}^{A}.\label{eq:first-order-constraint-simple-scheme}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The nature of this equation is remarkable.
 The 
\backslash
emph{constraint} yields a 
\backslash
emph{wave equation} for the fluctuations.
 Working out the component equations gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\tilde{\Delta}_{G}^{-1}\delta\varphi_{N} & =-J_{N}, & A=\left(g,N\right),\ c\neq N,\label{eq:phiN-eom-massless}\\
\tilde{\Delta}_{H}^{-1}\delta\varphi_{g} & =-J_{g}, & A=\left(g,N\right),\ c=N,\label{eq:phiG-eom-w-Higgs-propagator}\\
\tilde{\Delta}_{G}^{-1}\delta\varphi_{g} & =-J_{g}, & A=\left(g,g'\right),\ g,g'\neq N,\ c=g',c\neq g.\label{eq:phiG-eom-w-Goldstone-propagator}
\end{align}

\end_inset

 The desired linear response functions are then just the Green functions
 for these equations, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{NN}^{\phi J}\left(x,y\right)=-\tilde{\Delta}_{G}\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two major flaws with these equations.
 The first is a physical misprediction: 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\varphi_{N}$
\end_inset

 propagates masslessly due to the equilibrium Goldstone propagator even
 though the Higgs propagator has a non-zero mass.
 The second is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\varphi_{g}$
\end_inset

 is overdetermined, i.e.
 its initial value problem is ill posed.
 In the Fourier domain equations (
\backslash
ref{eq:phiG-eom-w-Higgs-propagator}) and (
\backslash
ref{eq:phiG-eom-w-Goldstone-propagator}) read 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left(p^{2}-m_{H}^{2}-\tilde{\Sigma}_{H}\left(p\right)\right)\delta\varphi_{g} & = & -J_{g},\\
\left(p^{2}-\tilde{\Sigma}_{G}\left(p\right)\right)\delta\varphi_{g} & = & -J_{g},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 which obviously only allows solutions if there are modes satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}^{2}+\tilde{\Sigma}_{H}\left(p\right)=\tilde{\Sigma}_{G}\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{g}$
\end_inset

 is only supported on these modes.
 If any other perturbation is applied or a solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}^{2}+\tilde{\Sigma}_{H}\left(p\right)=\tilde{\Sigma}_{G}\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 does not exist the system is inconsistent.
 This is clearly not the expected behavior physically.
 One can relax (
\backslash
ref{eq:phiG-eom-w-Higgs-propagator}) by using the projected constraint (
\backslash
ref{eq:projected-constraint}) instead of (
\backslash
ref{eq:simple-constraint}), however this leads to further difficulties as
 discussed in Appendix 
\backslash
ref{sec:The-Alternate-Constraint}.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is further danger lurking in the right hand sides of equations (
\backslash
ref{eq:si-eom-vev}) and (
\backslash
ref{eq:si-eom-delta}).
 Since the constraint procedure involves a limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\ell}\to\infty$
\end_inset

 there is a danger that terms on the right hand sides can diverge.
 Consider the expansion of the right hand side of (
\backslash
ref{eq:si-eom-vev}) to first order:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
\frac{i}{2}\int_{x}\delta\ell_{A}^{c}\left(x\right)\tilde{\Delta}_{ca}^{-1}\left(x,z\right)T_{ad}^{A}+\frac{i}{2}\int_{x}\tilde{\ell}_{A}^{c}\left(x\right)\delta\Delta_{ca}^{-1}\left(x,z\right)T_{ad}^{A}\\
-J_{d}\left(z\right)-\int_{w}K_{de}\left(z,w\right)\tilde{\varphi}_{e}\left(w\right).
\end{multline}

\end_inset

 Using (
\backslash
ref{eq:lagrange-multipliers}) the term proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\ell}$
\end_inset

 can be written 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\frac{1}{N-1}\tilde{\ell}_{eN}^{e}\left(P_{cg}^{\perp}\int_{x}\delta\Delta_{cg}^{-1}\left(x,z\right)\delta_{Nd}-P_{cd}^{\perp}\int_{x}\delta\Delta_{cN}^{-1}\left(x,z\right)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 which, for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\ell}_{eN}^{e}\to\infty$
\end_inset

 limit to exist, requires that the term in braces vanishes, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=\delta_{Nd}\int_{x}P_{cg}^{\perp}\delta\Delta_{cg}^{-1}\left(x,z\right)-P_{cd}^{\perp}\int_{x}\delta\Delta_{cN}^{-1}\left(x,z\right).\label{eq:secondary-constraint-phi-eom}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 A similar analysis for (
\backslash
ref{eq:si-eom-delta}) gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =vm_{G}^{2}\int_{x}\left(P_{ea}^{\perp}\delta\Delta_{ad}^{-1}\left(x,z\right)+\delta\Delta_{ea}^{-1}\left(w,x\right)P_{ad}^{\perp}\right)\nonumber \\
 & -P_{db}^{\perp}\delta_{eN}m_{G}^{2}\int_{y}\tilde{\Delta}_{H}^{-1}\left(w,y\right)\delta\varphi_{b}\left(y\right)\nonumber \\
 & +P_{de}^{\perp}m_{G}^{2}\int_{y}\tilde{\Delta}_{G}^{-1}\left(w,y\right)\delta\varphi_{N}\left(y\right).\label{eq:secondary-constraint-delta-eom}
\end{align}

\end_inset

 We call (
\backslash
ref{eq:secondary-constraint-phi-eom}) and (
\backslash
ref{eq:secondary-constraint-delta-eom}) the 
\backslash
emph{secondary} constraints of the scheme and, by contrast, equation (
\backslash
ref{eq:WI-first-order}) the 
\backslash
emph{primary} constraint 
\backslash
footnote{These should not to be confused with the terminology from Dirac's
 constrained quantization method.}.
 The secondary constraints must be enforced so that no divergences appear
 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\ell}\to\infty$
\end_inset

 limit of the equations of motion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that one can take 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}\to0$
\end_inset

 without any problems in (
\backslash
ref{eq:secondary-constraint-delta-eom}), so that constraint is satisfied
 identically.
 Similarly, using (
\backslash
ref{eq:variation-of-inverse-delta}), (
\backslash
ref{eq:secondary-constraint-phi-eom}) becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =m_{G}^{2}\int_{yw}\left(\delta_{dN}P_{cg}^{\perp}\delta\Delta_{cg}\left(y,w\right)\tilde{\Delta}_{G}^{-1}\left(w,z\right)\right.\nonumber \\
 & \left.-P_{de}^{\perp}\delta\Delta_{eN}\left(y,w\right)\tilde{\Delta}_{H}^{-1}\left(w,z\right)\right),
\end{align}

\end_inset

 which is also automatically satisfied in the 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}\to0$
\end_inset

 limit.
 The fact that the secondary constraints automatically vanish is a consequence
 of using the unprojected constraint (
\backslash
ref{eq:simple-constraint}).
 Had we used (
\backslash
ref{eq:projected-constraint}) instead, the troublesome equation of motion
 (
\backslash
ref{eq:phiG-eom-w-Higgs-propagator}) would be gone, but the secondary constraint
s become non-trivial and lead again to pathologies (see Appendix 
\backslash
ref{sec:The-Alternate-Constraint}).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Alternate Constraint Scheme
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}{
\end_layout

